Okay 👍 problem clear: **GitHub lo already `master` branch undi**, and you want to push your new code into that same existing `master`.

No need to create new branch — just **commit + push to existing master**.

---

# ✅ Correct steps to push to existing `master`

### 🔹 1. First check branch

```bash id="a1b2c3"
git branch
```

If you are NOT on master, switch:

```bash id="d4e5f6"
git switch master
```

---

### 🔹 2. Add your new code

```bash id="g7h8i9"
git add .
```

---

### 🔹 3. Commit changes

```bash id="j1k2l3"
git commit -m "updated code"
```

---

### 🔹 4. Push to existing master (IMPORTANT)

```bash id="m4n5o6"
git push origin master
```

---

# ⚠️ If it still says “master already exists” error

Sometimes issue `upstream` set avvakapothe:

### Fix:

```bash id="p7q8r9"
git push -u origin master
```

👉 This links local master with GitHub master.

---

# 🔥 If GitHub main branch is `main` (VERY COMMON NOW)

Check remote branches:

```bash id="s1t2u3"
git branch -r
```

If you see `origin/main` instead of `master`, then use:

```bash id="v4w5x6"
git push origin main
```

OR rename your local branch:

```bash id="y7z8a9"
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
```

